{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "SI Units",
      "simpleDefinition": "The international standard system of measurement used to ensure technical data is consistent worldwide.",
      "anchor": "The global language of measurement.",
      "misconception": "Thinking that imperial units like inches or pounds are used in electrical science calculations."
    },
    {
      "term": "Base Units",
      "simpleDefinition": "The seven fundamental units of measurement from which all others are built, such as the Metre, Kilogram, and Ampere.",
      "anchor": "The building blocks of measurement.",
      "misconception": "Believing that common electrical units like Volts or Watts are base units; they are actually derived from others."
    },
    {
      "term": "Derived Units",
      "simpleDefinition": "Units created by mathematically combining base units, such as the Watt (Power) or the Ohm (Resistance).",
      "anchor": "Combinations of base units.",
      "misconception": "Thinking derived units are less accurate than base units because they are 'calculated'."
    },
    {
      "term": "Current (I)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The flow of electrical charge through a conductor, measured in Amperes (A).",
      "anchor": "The flow of electrons.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the quantity symbol 'I' with the unit symbol 'A'."
    },
    {
      "term": "Voltage (V)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The electrical pressure or potential difference that pushes current through a circuit, measured in Volts (V).",
      "anchor": "Electrical push.",
      "misconception": "Describing voltage as 'flowing' through a wire; current flows, while voltage is the pressure behind it."
    },
    {
      "term": "Resistance (R)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The property of a material that opposes the flow of electric current, measured in Ohms (Ω).",
      "anchor": "Electrical friction.",
      "misconception": "Thinking resistance only exists in components called 'resistors' rather than in all conductors."
    },
    {
      "term": "Power (P)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The rate at which electrical energy is converted into another form, such as heat or light, measured in Watts (W).",
      "anchor": "Energy used per second.",
      "misconception": "Using the terms 'Power' and 'Energy' interchangeably; power is the rate, energy is the total amount."
    },
    {
      "term": "Frequency (f)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The number of complete cycles an alternating current (AC) makes in one second, measured in Hertz (Hz).",
      "anchor": "Cycles per second.",
      "misconception": "Thinking frequency applies to Direct Current (DC) systems."
    },
    {
      "term": "Impedance (Z)",
      "simpleDefinition": "The total opposition to current flow in an AC circuit, combining resistance and reactance, measured in Ohms (Ω).",
      "anchor": "Total AC opposition.",
      "misconception": "Believing impedance must have a different unit because it is different from resistance; both use Ohms."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "The quantity is the 'what', the unit is the 'how much'.",
    "SI units ensure every electrician is speaking the same language.",
    "Base units are the foundation; derived units are the structures built on them."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Confusing the quantity symbol (e.g., 'I') with the unit symbol (e.g., 'A').",
    "Assuming all electrical units are base units.",
    "Mixing up Power (Watts) and Energy (Joules)."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "202-2a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "General SI Units",
      "objective": "Identify base and derived SI units for physical measurements.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the electrical industry, precision is everything. We use the International System of Units (SI) to ensure every measurement is consistent worldwide. Think of SI units as the global language of measurement. There are two types you need to know: Base Units and Derived Units. Base units are the fundamental building blocks of measurement. For example, the Metre (m) measures length, the Kilogram (kg) measures mass, and the Second (s) measures time. Even temperature has a base unit called the Kelvin (K), though we often use Celsius in daily work.",
        "Derived units are structures built by mathematically combining base units. If you multiply length by width, you get Area, measured in square metres (m²). If you factor in depth, you get Volume, measured in cubic metres (m³). Velocity is another derived unit, measuring distance over time (m/s), while Density compares mass to volume (kg/m³). Understanding these standards prevents catastrophic calculation errors when designing or installing electrical systems. Always remember: the base units are the foundation, and derived units are the combinations used for more complex physical properties."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the difference between a single fundamental measurement like a metre and a combined measurement like metres per second."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Electrical Quantities and Units",
      "objective": "Identify the specific SI units associated with electrical quantities.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "As an electrician, you must distinguish between the 'quantity' (the thing you are measuring) and the 'unit' (the standard used to measure it). A common mistake is confusing the quantity symbol with the unit symbol. For instance, Current is the quantity (symbol 'I'), but it is measured in Amperes (unit symbol 'A'). Voltage (V) is the electrical pressure measured in Volts (V). Resistance (R) is the opposition to current flow, measured in Ohms (Ω). In AC circuits, we also deal with Impedance (Z), which is the total opposition to current; even though it is a different concept from resistance, it is also measured in Ohms (Ω).",
        "Power (P) is the rate of energy use, measured in Watts (W), while the total amount of energy used is measured in Joules (J). Frequency (f), the number of cycles per second in AC, is measured in Hertz (Hz). Other specific quantities include Inductance (measured in Henrys), Capacitance (measured in Farads), and Resistivity (Ohm-metres). Finally, Power Factor is a ratio used to describe efficiency; because it is a ratio, it has no unit at all. Using these terms precisely ensures you can communicate technical data accurately on site."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that the quantity is the 'what' (like Resistance) and the unit is the 'how much' (like Ohms)."
    }
  ]
}

